The paper deals with theoretical models for real-world networks, which is a topic that falls under the scope of several arXiv CS sub-categories. 

- cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) is a likely category since the paper deals with random graph models and their structural properties. 
- cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is also a likely category since the paper mentions social networks as an example of real-world networks. 
- cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) is a possible category since the paper mentions the internet infrastructure as an example of real-world networks, which could be related to network optimization and routing problems. 
- cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) is a possible category since the paper deals with graph models and their algorithmic properties. 
- cs.IT (Information Theory) is a possible category since the paper mentions compressing GIRGs using an expected linear number of bits.
